### Feature: Variable-Length Offset/Length Encoding → ZXL5

#### Problem
ZXL4 encoded every match with a fixed 3-byte offset + 2-byte length = 5 parameter
bytes per exact/delta match token, regardless of actual offset magnitude.
PE binaries have strong temporal locality — many matches reference data only
dozens or hundreds of bytes back. Paying 3 bytes for an offset of 12 was wasteful.

#### Solution
Introduced variable-length encoding for both offset and length fields:
- 1-byte offset (TOK_EXACT1): covers offsets 1–255
- 2-byte offset (TOK_EXACT2): covers offsets 256–65535
- 3-byte offset (TOK_EXACT/TOK_DELTA): covers 65536–1MB (fallback)
- 1-byte length (most tokens): covers len-MIN_MATCH 0–255 (matches 4–259 bytes)
- 2-byte length (TOK_EXACT/TOK_DELTA): for rare very long matches

Same scheme for delta matches: TOK_DELTA1, TOK_DELTA2.
REP tokens (REP0/1/2) also changed from 2-byte to 1-byte length. Long-length REP
matches (len-4 >= 256) fall through to TOK_EXACT with the REP offset — the
decompressor's rep[] cache is still updated correctly via TOK_EXACT.

#### Token Table Changes (ZXL4 → ZXL5)
Magic: 0x344C585A ("ZXL4") → 0x354C585A ("ZXL5")
Max literal run: 251 bytes (token 0xFA) → 247 bytes (token 0xF6)
Freed 4 token slots (0xF7–0xFA) for new token types:

  0x00..0xF6  literal run (run=tok+1, 1..247 bytes)
  0xF7        TOK_EXACT1:  [1]offset, [1]len-MIN_MATCH
  0xF8        TOK_EXACT2:  [2]offset, [1]len-MIN_MATCH
  0xF9        TOK_DELTA1:  [1]mtype, [1]delta, [1]offset, [1]len-MIN_MATCH
  0xFA        TOK_DELTA2:  [1]mtype, [1]delta, [2]offset, [1]len-MIN_MATCH
  0xFB        TOK_REP0:    [1]len-MIN_MATCH  (was 2 bytes)
  0xFC        TOK_REP1:    [1]len-MIN_MATCH  (was 2 bytes)
  0xFD        TOK_REP2:    [1]len-MIN_MATCH  (was 2 bytes)
  0xFE        TOK_EXACT:   [3]offset, [2]len-MIN_MATCH  (fallback)
  0xFF        TOK_DELTA:   [1]mtype,[1]delta,[3]offset,[2]len-MIN_MATCH

#### DP Overhead: 2 values → 6 values
ZXL4 used one overhead estimate per match type (ovhd_exact, ovhd_delta).
ZXL5 uses six, one per offset-size class per match type:
  ovhd_exact1, ovhd_exact2, ovhd_exact
  ovhd_delta1, ovhd_delta2, ovhd_delta

Each is computed in pass 1 from real token frequencies:
  overhead = -log2(count[tok] / total_tokens) + n_params × h_tok

The DP backward pass selects the correct overhead based on each candidate match's
actual offset and length, giving more accurate parse decisions — especially for
short-offset matches which are now correctly seen as much cheaper.

