### Feature: Context-Aware DP Literal Costs (attempted, reverted)

#### Approach
Extended the greedy pre-pass to also track prev_out, filling est_ctx[i] =
(prev_out >> N_LIT_CTX_SHIFT) as an estimate of the 8-way literal context at
each position. After pass-1 forward trace, rebuilt ctx_sym_cost[8][256] from
the actual pass-1 literal distribution (lit_buf / lit_ctx_buf). Pass-2 DP used
ctx_sym_cost[est_ctx[u]][byte] instead of global sym_cost[byte].

#### Result
  ntdll.dll    : 0.4826  (was 0.4803, +0.23 pts WORSE)
  kernel32.dll : 0.4798  (was 0.4786, +0.12 pts WORSE)
  user32.dll   : 0.3910  (was 0.3909, +0.01 pts WORSE)

Regressed across the board. Reverted.

#### Root cause
The greedy pre-pass sets est_ctx for interior match positions using the context
before the match (approximation). When the DP decides NOT to take the match and
encodes those positions as literals instead, the actual context differs from
est_ctx. The DP then makes wrong decisions based on stale context costs.
The circular dependency (context depends on parse, parse depends on context)
makes this approach unreliable without a full state-tracking DP.

### Feature: Larger Hash Table (16-bit → 18-bit, 64K → 256K buckets)

MatchCtx head tables: 64K → 256K entries each. With 512K window entries, the average
chain length per bucket drops from ~8 to ~2. Fewer collisions → better match candidates
at the same chain depth. MatchCtx RAM: 3MB → 9MB. Side effect: chains terminate sooner
on average, which slightly speeds up compression.

#### Result
  ntdll.dll    : 0.4801  (was 0.4803, −0.02 pts, faster: 0.2→0.4 MB/s)
  kernel32.dll : 0.4786  (no change, faster: 0.6→0.8 MB/s)
  user32.dll   : 0.3909  (no change, faster: 0.4→0.6 MB/s)

Tiny ratio gain + compression speed improvement. Kept.

### Attempted: Residual sym_cost + run token overhead (attempted, reverted)

Tried two DP cost improvements:
1. Rebuild sym_cost from pass-1 residual literals (matches remove low-entropy bytes,
   residual is higher entropy → more accurate DP literal costs)
2. Add amortized run-token overhead per literal (h_tok / avg_run_len bits per literal,
   correcting for run tokens not accounted in sym_cost)

Both individually and combined caused severe regressions (+0.5–1.0 pts worse).

Root cause: circular dependency. sym_cost from pass-1 residuals models a different parse
than the pass-2 DP will produce. Wrong context estimates cause the DP to make decisions
that don't match the actual encoding costs.

### Feature: 3-Pass Optimal DP + Residual sym_cost on Pass 3

Instead of rebuilding sym_cost after pass 0 (unstable), run 3 passes:
- Pass 0 → 1: rough overheads → real overheads (same as before)
- Pass 1 → 2: real overheads AGAIN (from pass-1 token stream) + rebuild sym_cost from
  pass-1 residual literals. Pass 1 and 2 are much closer in parse quality, so residual
  distribution from pass 1 accurately models pass 2's literal costs.
- Pass 2: final output

#### Result
  ntdll.dll    : 0.4802  (essentially unchanged)
  kernel32.dll : 0.4786  (unchanged)
  user32.dll   : 0.3899  (was 0.3909, −0.10 pts)
  Compress speed: ~25% slower (extra pass)

user32 gains 0.10 pts — now only 0.23 pts behind gzip-6. ntdll/kernel32 unchanged.
The residual sym_cost helps more on user32 (data-heavy, more stable literal distribution
between passes) than ntdll/kernel32 (code-heavy, more volatile match/literal split).

