### Feature: Extended BCJ — Conditional Near Jumps (0F 80..8F)

#### Problem
ZXL's BCJ filter converted E8/E9 (CALL/JMP rel32) relative operands to absolute. In x64
PE code, conditional near jumps (JE/JNE/JB/JA/JS/JL/JG etc.) — encoded as 0F 80..8F
with a 4-byte relative offset — are equally common but were not filtered.

#### Solution
Extended bcj_x86_forward/inverse to detect `[0F][8x]` prefixes (x in 0..F, covering all
16 conditional near jump variants) and convert their 4-byte offset (at buf[i+2..i+5])
from relative to absolute. The skip-ahead after detecting a prefix (i += 5) prevents
the 4 offset bytes from being misidentified as new opcodes, keeping the transform
invertible. The 2-byte opcode check requires `i + 6 <= len` to guard the 6-byte instruction.

#### Benchmark Results

  ntdll.dll    : 0.4630  (was 0.4634, −0.04 pts)
  kernel32.dll : 0.4605  (was 0.4620, −0.15 pts)
  user32.dll   : 0.3781  (was 0.3790, −0.09 pts)

  kernel32 gained most (code-heavy, dense conditional branches).
  user32 also gained (data sections have fewer Jcc, but some code).

  Round-trip: PASS

